<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ai-assisted-accessibility">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>WCAG 2.2 AA compliance pipeline: AI-enhanced automated scanning (axe-core, Lighthouse) catches 60-70% of issues; remaining 30-40% need human + AT testing.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
      <tag>wcag</tag>
      <tag>a11y-testing</tag>
      <tag>compliance</tag>
      <tag>automation</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI-Assisted Accessibility</title>
    <summary>Pipeline for WCAG 2.2 AA compliance using AI-enhanced automated scanning (axe-core, Lighthouse, pa11y) as the first pass, followed by manual assistive technology testing for interactive components and cognitive accessibility. Automated tools catch 60-70% of auditable issues; the remaining 30-40% require human + AT verification.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Manual accessibility audits are expert-intensive and expensive. AI-enhanced tools (axe DevTools, Deque) reduce false positives and suggest code fixes in context, cutting remediation time. Treating AI-only results as sufficient produces incomplete compliance; the pipeline enforces the correct sequence — automate first, then verify with real AT.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sprint includes new UI components that must meet WCAG 2.2 AA before merge</item>
        <item>Accessibility audit needed for an existing product with no prior testing baseline</item>
        <item>Small team without a dedicated accessibility specialist (AI augments coverage)</item>
        <item>Preparing a VPAT for enterprise procurement</item>
        <item>Video/audio content being published (ADA Title II 2026 captions/audio descriptions required)</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Treating AI overlay widgets as a substitute for fixing underlying code — overlays are not compliant solutions</item>
        <item>As the only testing method — automated tools miss 30-40% of issues</item>
        <item>Complex interactive patterns (drag-and-drop, data grids, custom widgets) — AI scoring is unreliable; manual AT testing required</item>
        <item>When user testing with people with disabilities is scheduled — do automated pass first, fix, then test with real users</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Audit Pipeline Order">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run automated scanning first (axe-core, Lighthouse, pa11y) to clear issues detectable by tooling, then do manual assistive technology testing for interactive components. Never reverse the order.</statement>
        <rationale>Running AT testing before automated scanning wastes expert time on low-hanging fruit that tools catch in minutes. Automated first, human second is the efficient sequence.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Set axe-core as a CI/CD gate failing builds on critical and serious violations only. Moderate and minor violations produce warnings. Do not gate on all violation levels — it creates alert fatigue.</statement>
        <rationale>Blocking on every violation, including cosmetic issues, causes teams to disable the gate. Impact-based gating keeps the signal actionable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Test interactive components (drag-and-drop, data grids, custom widgets, modal dialogs) with actual screen readers (NVDA + Chrome, VoiceOver + Safari) — no automated tool substitutes for AT testing of dynamic interactions.</statement>
        <rationale>ARIA role validation requires runtime context. Automated tools miss dynamic state changes, focus management failures, and live region announcements.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Tool Coverage Limits">
      <rule>
        <statement>Document that automated tools cover approximately 60-70% of WCAG 2.2 auditable criteria. The remaining 30-40% — cognitive accessibility, plain language, reading level, complex chart alt text, and custom widget behavior — requires human evaluation.</statement>
        <rationale>Presenting automated results as full compliance creates legal exposure. VPAT authors and QA engineers must know the coverage boundary.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using AI overlay widgets (UserWay, AccessiBe) as the sole compliance strategy</description>
        <reason>Overlays do not fix underlying code issues. They are runtime patches that fail when JavaScript is disabled or with certain AT combinations. Legal challenges have succeeded against overlay-only compliance claims.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="VPAT Guidance">
      <rule>
        <statement>A VPAT (Voluntary Product Accessibility Template) drafted by an agent requires human accessibility expert review and sign-off before publishing. Agents draft; humans certify.</statement>
        <rationale>No AI tool generates a legally defensible VPAT without human review. Incorrect conformance claims create procurement and legal risk.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep VPAT drafts versioned alongside product releases. An outdated VPAT from a prior version creates legal exposure for the current version.</statement>
        <rationale>Procurement and legal teams rely on current VPATs. A stale document that no longer reflects the product's accessibility state is worse than no document.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools">
      <list>
        <item>axe-core (via Playwright/Puppeteer) — automated WCAG scanning with JSON output; npm install axe-core</item>
        <item>lighthouse CLI — Chrome-based a11y + performance audit; npm install -g lighthouse</item>
        <item>pa11y — command-line a11y testing with multiple runner support; npm install -g pa11y</item>
        <item>colour-contrast-checker — CLI contrast ratio verification; npm package</item>
        <item>htmlcs — HTML_CodeSniffer for WCAG rule checking; squizlabs.github.io/HTML_CodeSniffer</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Key Services">
      <list>
        <item>Deque axe DevTools (SaaS) — AI-powered false-positive reduction, enterprise scanning, REST API + CLI; industry standard</item>
        <item>Level Access (SaaS) — "Ask Level AI" chatbot for issue Q&amp;A; enterprise VPAT generation; partial API</item>
        <item>3Play Media (SaaS) — AI-enabled captions and audio descriptions; REST API; agent can submit video, poll for output</item>
        <item>Siteimprove (SaaS) — continuous monitoring; good for regression detection in CI/CD; REST API</item>
        <item>Accessibility Insights (OSS, Microsoft) — browser extension; excellent for manual testing; not agent-drivable</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Workflow">
      <rule>
        <statement>An agent can run axe-core via Playwright, parse the violation JSON, prioritize by WCAG criterion and user impact, and generate a developer-facing remediation brief with before/after code snippets. The agent must never mark issues as resolved — only humans or automated regression tests close findings.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents provide scale and consistency in the audit-and-brief phase; human verification is required for the close phase because AT testing and accessibility judgment require human context.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent runs axe-core without handling auth flows, cookie consent banners, or dynamic content loading</description>
        <reason>All three interfere with scan results. Agents must handle authentication, dismiss consent banners, and wait for dynamic content before running axe.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent maps violations to incorrect WCAG criteria (e.g., citing 1.4.3 Contrast for a keyboard navigation issue)</description>
        <reason>LLMs confidently produce incorrect criterion references. Always validate criterion mappings against the WCAG 2.2 spec or a verified tool output before including in a report.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent generates generic, keyword-stuffed alt text for complex charts and infographics</description>
        <reason>AI alt text defaults to describing the visual appearance, not the data or meaning. Prompt explicitly for functional, descriptive alt text that conveys the chart's insight.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent scans only the landing page of an SPA, missing component-level violations on navigated routes</description>
        <reason>SPA frameworks rebuild the DOM on navigation. Agents must trigger navigation events and re-run axe on each route.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent marks an ARIA-dependent issue resolved without AT verification</description>
        <reason>Assistive technology behavior (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver) diverges significantly from automated tool predictions. AT-dependent issues require AT verification before closing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <rule>
        <statement>A Claude subagent can run a multi-step accessibility audit pipeline: invoke axe-core or Lighthouse programmatically, parse the JSON output, prioritize issues by WCAG criterion and user impact, and generate a developer-facing remediation brief with code snippets. The agent should never mark issues as resolved — only humans or automated regression tests can close findings. For VPAT generation, the agent drafts the document; a human accessibility expert must review each criterion.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents provide consistency and scale in the detection and brief phase. Human review is essential for the certification phase since AT testing requires specialist knowledge and legal accountability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Recommended subagents: custom a11y-auditor agent (runs axe-core via Playwright, parses results, generates prioritized issue list with fix suggestions); faion-sdd-executor-agent (executes accessibility remediation tasks defined in an SDD implementation plan).</statement>
        <rationale>Subagent specialization keeps complexity bounded and makes audit and remediation tasks independently testable and auditable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Prompt Patterns for Agents">
      <example type="good" title="Audit Results Mapping Prompt">
        <p>You are an accessibility engineer. Analyze the following axe-core JSON output for violations. For each violation: 1. Map to the specific WCAG 2.2 success criterion (e.g., 1.4.3 Contrast). 2. Rate impact: critical / serious / moderate / minor. 3. Provide a concrete code fix (before/after). 4. Flag any that require human AT testing to verify. Return as Markdown table plus code blocks.</p>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="VPAT Draft Prompt">
        <p>Draft a WCAG 2.2 AA conformance statement for this product: Product: {{product_name}}, Test date: {{date}}, Known issues: {{issues_list}}. Format as a standard VPAT 2.5 summary section. Flag all items that require human legal review before publishing.</p>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Run automated scan first to clear low-hanging fruit, then do manual AT testing — don't reverse the order</item>
        <item>Set axe-core as a CI/CD gate; fail builds on critical or serious violations only to avoid alert fatigue</item>
        <item>Generate developer-facing briefs (not raw JSON) from audit tools — raw axe output is not actionable for most developers</item>
        <item>Test with actual screen readers (NVDA + Chrome, VoiceOver + Safari) for interactive components — no automated tool substitutes</item>
        <item>Keep VPAT drafts versioned alongside product releases — outdated VPATs create legal exposure</item>
        <item>Caption quality from AI tools degrades significantly for technical jargon, proper nouns, and non-English content — always human-review captions</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Limitations">
      <list>
        <item>Automated tools (including AI-enhanced ones) cannot assess cognitive accessibility, plain language, or reading level</item>
        <item>Color contrast checkers fail on gradient backgrounds and complex imagery — requires human review</item>
        <item>AI alt-text generation for complex charts/infographics is often too generic to be useful to screen reader users</item>
        <item>ARIA role validation requires runtime context; static analysis tools miss dynamic state changes</item>
        <item>False-negative rates on custom JavaScript widgets are high — AI flags standard HTML well, custom components poorly</item>
        <item>No AI tool generates a legally defensible VPAT without human review and sign-off</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/axe-playwright-runner.py" purpose="Run axe-core via Playwright to get violation JSON for audit input"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-audit-results.txt" purpose="Agent prompt: process axe JSON into developer-facing remediation brief"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-vpat-draft.txt" purpose="Agent prompt: draft WCAG 2.2 AA conformance statement from known issues"/>
    </templates>
